{"id": "ei1izu", "title": "Closing spreads today and tax implications.", "selftext": "This is posted over in r/options but I think it is worth repeating here since it has ruined my plans for today and I feel the need to ruin your plans too.\n\n&amp;#x200B;\n\n **Be careful about the unexpected tax consequences of closing spreads today (Dec 31)**\n\n&amp;#x200B;\n\nFor some stupid reason, short positions (whether in stocks/ETFs or stock/ETF/index options) fall in the tax year of the settlement date instead of the trade date:\n\n&gt;**A WORD ABOUT LONG OR SHORT OPTIONS SPREADS**  \nPlease note that a long or short vertical, iron condor, calendar, diagonal, butterfly, etc. consist of a long leg and a short leg. As a result, **if you wish to close an option spread to count towards the 2019 tax year, then the spread must be closed by Monday, December 30, 2019, due to the T+1 settlement time of the short leg**. As a result, any options spread closed after the deadline will result in the long leg reporting in the 2019 tax year and the short leg reporting in the 2020 tax year.\n\nSource: [https://tastyworks.freshdesk.com/support/solutions/articles/43000550645-position-reporting-for-end-of-year-taxes](https://tastyworks.freshdesk.com/support/solutions/articles/43000550645-position-reporting-for-end-of-year-taxes)\n\nIf you roll a big options position comprised of spreads today you might end up having an unpleasant surprise when you file your taxes!", "created_utc": 1577790302, "permalink": "/r/wallstreetbets/comments/ei1izu/closing_spreads_today_and_tax_implications/", "is_self": true}